the experiences of Afrodescendants in plurinational Bolivia and offers a fresh perspective on the social and political transformations shaping the country as a whole. Moritz Heck analyzes Afrobolivian social and cultural practices at the intersections of local communities, politics, and the law, shedding light on novel articulations of Afrobolivianity and evolving processes of collective identification. This study also contributes to broader anthropological debates on blackness and indigeneity in Latin America by pointing out their conceptual entanglements and continuous interactions in political and social practice.  afunded by Backlisttransformation EOSC Future  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlackszBoliviaxEthnic relations. 0aBlackszBoliviaxPolitics and government. 0aBlackszBolivia. 0aSpanish languagexDialectszBoliviaxDeterminers. 0aSpanish languagexDialectszBoliviaxGrammar. 0aSpanish languagexDialectszBolivia. 0aSpanish languagezBoliviaxForeign elementsxAfrican. 4aAfrican Diaspora. 4aAfrodescendants. 4aAmerica. 4aCultural Anthropology. 4aCultural History. 4aEthnicity. 4aEthnology. 4aIndigeneity. 4aPlurinationality. 4aRacism. 4aSocial Movements. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAfrican Diaspora.  aAfrodescendants.  aAmerica.  aCultural Anthropology.  aCultural History.  aEthnicity.  aEthnology.  aIndigeneity.  aPlurinationality.  aRacism.  aSocial Movements.2 aBacklisttransformation EOSC Futureefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEB